<BR> 

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://www.historymuseum.ca/cmc/exhibitions/aborig/fp/fpz2f34e.shtml
">Reach of the Horned Serpent</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The legend of Weewillmekq/Jipijka'm, the Wabanaki horned serpent.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.indigenouspeople.net/fourwind.htm
">The Giant and the Four Wind Brothers</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Folktale about the adventures of a Penobscot giant.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.indigenouspeople.net/bearfami.htm
">Legend of the Bear Family</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Origin of the Penobscot Bear Clan.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.bigorrin.org/archive41.htm
">Arrowhead Finger</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Legend of a Penobscot girl who bore a medicine child.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20070917091403/http://www.lib.unb.ca/Texts/QWERTY/Qweb/qwerte/mic_mal/ractxten.htm
">Raccoon Learns A Lesson</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Raccoon plays a trick on two blind men. In English and Mi'kmaq.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.native-languages.org/penobscotstory2.htm
">Pamola, A Penobscot Legend</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Penobscot story about a woman who married the bird spirit of Mount Katahdin.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.native-languages.org/mikmaqstory2.htm
">Nukumi and Fire</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The origin of Glooscap's grandmother.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20041105075908fw_/http://www.lib.unb.ca/Texts/QWERTY/Qweb/qwerte/mic_mal/vistxten.htm
">The Creator Visits</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The Creator rewards a family's generosity. 
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20120315140844/http://www.ucan-online.org/legend.asp?legend=4712&category=7
">Indian Summer</a></b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.sacred-texts.com/nam/ne/al/al32.htm
">Nibubalnoba, the Indian Summer</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Legends about the origins of "Indian summer," the brief recurrence of summer-like weather before the snows fall.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20041101182825fw_/http://www.lib.unb.ca/Texts/QWERTY/Qweb/qwerte/mic_mal/b2gtxten.htm
">Glooscap Turns Bad Into Good</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Glooscap creates landmarks on the St. John River. 
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
https://web.archive.org/web/20110311134320/http://boydenlake.com/Fokelore.asp
">Weewilmekq and Kitchi-at'Husis</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A fight between two Wabanaki water monsters.
<BR>

<H2><U>
<a name="books">Recommended Books on Wabanaki Mythology</a>
</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0892552484/natilangofthe-20
">On the Trail of Elder Brother</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Excellent collection of traditional Koluscap stories told by a Mi'kmaq author.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1885772254/natilangofthe-20
">Seven Eyes, Seven Legs: Supernatural Stories of the Abenaki</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A good coffee-table book of myths and folktales told and illustrated by an Abenaki artist.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1888034017/natilangofthe-20
">Giants of the Dawnland</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Another great collection of Wabanaki legends told by a Penobscot Indian author.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0803729774/natilangofthe-20
">Raccoon's Last Race</a>:</b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <B><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0525651640/natilangofthe-20
">Gluskabe and the Four Wishes</a>:</b> <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Children's picture books illustrating Abenaki legends, by acclaimed Native storyteller Joseph Bruchac.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0884482707/natilangofthe-20
">Thanks To The Animals</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Charming picture book telling a Passamaquoddy story about a lost child protected by the animals of the forest.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0698116267/natilangofthe-20
">The Rough-Faced Girl</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Picture book based on the Mi'kmaq-Maliseet Cinderella story.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B0000017QT/natilangofthe-20
">Echoes of the Night</a>:</b> <IMG SRC="star.gif" ALT="*"> <b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0938756265/natilangofthe-20
">Gluskap Stories</a>:</b> <br> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Audio recordings of Wabanaki storytelling.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0803293380/natilangofthe-20
">Algonquian Spirit</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Rich anthology of stories, songs, and oral history from the Wabanaki and other Algonquian tribes.  
<BR>

